# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: elixir
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elixir/basic-types] In this chapter we will learn more about Elixir basic types: integers, floats, booleans, atoms, and strings.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Other data types, such as lists and tuples, will be explored in the next chapter.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Notice that `10 / 2` returned a float `5.0` instead of an integer `5`.
[src:elixir/basic-types] In Elixir, the operator `/` always returns a float.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Notice that Elixir allows you to drop the parentheses when invoking functions that expect one or more arguments.
[src:elixir/basic-types] This feature gives a cleaner syntax when writing declarations and control-flow constructs.
[src:elixir/basic-types] However, Elixir developers generally prefer to use parentheses.
[src:elixir/basic-types] You can invoke the `round` function to get the closest integer to a given float, or the `trunc` function to get the integer part of a float.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Finally, as we work with different data types, we will learn that Elixir provides several predicate functions to check for the type of a value.
[src:elixir/basic-types] You can also use `is_float` or `is_number` to check, respectively, if an argument is a float, or either an integer or float.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Elixir also provides three boolean operators: `or`, `and`, and `not`.
[src:elixir/basic-types] `or` and `and` are short-circuit operators.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Elixir also provides the concept of `nil`, to indicate the absence of a value, and a set of logical operators that also manipulate `nil`: `||/2`, `&&/2`, and `!/1`.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Similarly, values like `0` and `""`, which some other programming languages consider to be "falsy", are also "truthy" in Elixir.
[src:elixir/basic-types] As a rule of thumb, use `and`, `or` and `not` when you are expecting booleans.
[src:elixir/basic-types] If any of the arguments are non-boolean, use `&&`, `||` and `!`.
[src:elixir/basic-types] An atom is a constant whose value is its own name.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Some other languages call these symbols.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Atoms are equal if their names are equal.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Often they are used to express the state of an operation, by using values such as `:ok` and `:error`.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Elixir allows you to skip the leading `:` for the atoms `false`, `true` and `nil`.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Notice that the `IO.puts` function returns the atom `:ok` after printing.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Notice that the number of bytes in that string is 6, even though it has 5 graphemes.
[src:elixir/basic-types] That's because the grapheme "ö" takes 2 bytes to be represented in UTF-8.
[src:elixir/basic-types] The comparison operators in Elixir can compare across any data type.
[src:elixir/basic-types] We say these operators perform *structural comparison*.
[src:elixir/basic-types] For more information, you can read our documentation on Structural vs Semantic comparisons.
[src:elixir/basic-types] Elixir also provides data-types for expressing collections, such as lists and tuples, which we'll learn next.
[src:elixir/basic-types] When we talk about concurrency and fault-tolerance via processes, we will also discuss ports, pids, and references, but that will come in later chapters.
[src:elixir/elixir-programming-language] The community organizes yearly events in the United States, Europe, and Japan, as well as minor local events and conferences.
[src:elixir/elixir-programming-language] José Valim created the Elixir programming language as a research and development project at Plataformatec.
[src:elixir/elixir-programming-language] His goals were to enable higher extensibility and productivity in the Erlang VM while maintaining compatibility with Erlang's ecosystem.
[src:elixir/elixir-programming-language] Elixir is aimed at large-scale sites and apps.
[src:elixir/elixir-programming-language] It uses features of Ruby, Erlang, and Clojure to develop a high-concurrency and low-latency language.
[src:elixir/elixir-programming-language] It was designed to handle large data volumes.
[src:elixir/elixir-programming-language] Elixir is also used in telecommunications, e-commerce, and finance.
[src:elixir/elixir-programming-language] In 2021, the Numerical Elixir effort was announced with the goal of bringing machine learning, neural networks, GPU compilation, data processing, and computational notebooks to the Elixir ecosystem.
[src:elixir/elixir-programming-language] The following examples can be run in an `iex` shell or saved in a file and run from the command line by typing `elixir *<filename>*`.
[src:elixir/introduction] This guide will teach you about Elixir fundamentals - the language syntax, how to define modules, the common data structures in the language, and more.
[src:elixir/introduction] This chapter will focus on ensuring that Elixir is installed and that you can successfully run Elixir's Interactive Shell, called IEx.
[src:elixir/introduction] If you haven't yet installed Elixir, visit our installation page.
[src:elixir/introduction] Once you are done, you can run `elixir --version` to get the current Elixir version.
[src:elixir/introduction] If you are looking for other resources for learning Elixir, you can also consult the learning page of the official website.
[src:elixir/introduction] When you install Elixir, you will have three new command line executables: `iex`, `elixir` and `elixirc`.
[src:elixir/introduction] For now, let's start by running `iex` (or `iex.bat` if you are on Windows PowerShell, where `iex` is a PowerShell command) which stands for Interactive Elixir.
[src:elixir/introduction] In interactive mode, we can type any Elixir expression and get its result.
[src:elixir/introduction] Let's warm up with some basic expressions.
[src:elixir/introduction] Please note that some details like version numbers may differ a bit in your session, that's not important.
[src:elixir/introduction] By executing the code above, you should evaluate expressions and see their results.
[src:elixir/introduction] We will use the interactive shell quite a lot in the next chapters to get a bit more familiar with the language constructs and basic types, starting in the next chapter.
[src:elixir/introduction] After getting familiar with the basics of the language you may want to try writing simple programs.
[src:elixir/introduction] `iex` and `elixir` are all we need to learn the main language concepts.
[src:elixir/introduction] There is a separate guide named "Mix and OTP guide" that explores how to actually create, manage, and test full-blown Elixir projects.
[src:elixir/introduction] For now, let's move on to learn the basic data types in the language.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] In Elixir we group several functions into modules.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] In order to create our own modules in Elixir, we use the `defmodule` macro.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] The first letter of a module name (an alias, as described further down) must be in uppercase.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] We use the `def` macro to define functions in that module.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] In this chapter we will define our own modules, with different levels of complexity.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] As our examples get longer in size, it can be tricky to type them all in the shell, so we will resort more frequently to scripting.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Elixir has two file extensions `.ex` (Elixir) and `.exs` (Elixir scripts).
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Elixir treats both files exactly the same way, the only difference is in intention.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] `.ex` files are meant to be compiled while `.exs` files are used for scripting.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] And then have direct access to the `Math` module.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Inside a module, we can define functions with `def/2` and private functions with `defp/2`.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] A function defined with `def/2` can be invoked from other modules while a private function can only be invoked locally.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Function declarations also support guards and multiple clauses.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] If a function has several clauses, Elixir will try each clause until it finds one that matches.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] The trailing question mark in `zero?` means that this function returns a boolean.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] To learn more about the naming conventions for modules, function names, variables and more in Elixir, see Naming Conventions.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Giving an argument that does not match any of the clauses raises an error.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Similar to constructs like `if`, function definitions support both `do:` and `do`-block syntax, as we learned in the previous chapter.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] You may use `do:` for one-liners but always use `do`-blocks for functions spanning multiple lines.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] If you prefer to be consistent, you can use `do`-blocks throughout your codebase.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Any expression is allowed to serve as a default value, but it won't be evaluated during the function definition.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Function heads cannot have patterns nor guards.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] They may only define the argument names and their default values.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] An alias in Elixir is a capitalized identifier (like `String`, `Keyword`, etc) which is converted to an atom during compilation.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] By using the `alias/2` directive, we are changing the atom the alias expands to.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Aliases expand to atoms because in the Erlang Virtual Machine (and consequently Elixir) modules are always represented by atoms.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] By namespacing those atoms, Elixir modules avoid conflicting with existing Erlang modules.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] Now that we have talked about aliases, we can talk about nesting and how it works in Elixir.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] The example above will define two modules: `Foo` and `Foo.Bar`.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] The second can be accessed as `Bar` inside `Foo` as long as they are in the same lexical scope.
[src:elixir/modules-and-functions] You don't have to define the `Foo` module before defining the `Foo.Bar` module, as they are effectively independent.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] In this chapter, we will learn why the `=` operator in Elixir is called the match operator and how to use it to pattern match inside data structures.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] We will learn about the pin operator `^` used to access previously bound values.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] In Elixir, the `=` operator is actually called *the match operator*.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] Notice that `1 = x` is a valid expression, and it matched because both the left and right side are equal to `1`.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] When the sides do not match, a `MatchError` is raised.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] The match operator is not only used to match against simple values, but it is also useful for destructuring more complex data types.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] More interestingly, we can match on specific values.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] In some cases, you don't care about a particular value in a pattern.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] It is a common practice to bind those values to the underscore, `_`.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] The variable `_` is special in that it can never be read from.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] Although pattern matching allows us to build powerful constructs, its usage is limited.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] For instance, you cannot make function calls on the left side of a match.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] Pattern matching allows developers to easily destructure data types such as tuples and lists.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] As we will see in the following chapters, it is one of the foundations of recursion in Elixir and applies to other types as well, like maps and binaries.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] However, there are times when we don't want variables to be rebound.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] Use the pin operator `^` when you want to pattern match against a variable's *existing value* rather than rebinding the variable.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] Notice that we even see the exact same error message.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] This finishes our introduction to pattern matching.
[src:elixir/pattern-matching] As we will see in the next chapter, pattern matching is very common in many language constructs and they can be further augmented with guards.
[src:elixir/processes] In Elixir, all code runs inside processes.
[src:elixir/processes] Processes are isolated from each other, run concurrent to one another and communicate via message passing.
[src:elixir/processes] Processes are not only the basis for concurrency in Elixir, but they also provide the means for building distributed and fault-tolerant programs.
[src:elixir/processes] Elixir's processes should not be confused with operating system processes.
[src:elixir/processes] Processes in Elixir are extremely lightweight in terms of memory and CPU (even compared to threads as used in many other programming languages).
[src:elixir/processes] Because of this, it is not uncommon to have tens or even hundreds of thousands of processes running simultaneously.
[src:elixir/processes] In this chapter, we will learn about the basic constructs for spawning new processes, as well as sending and receiving messages between processes.
[src:elixir/processes] `spawn/1` takes a function which it will execute in another process.
[src:elixir/processes] Notice `spawn/1` returns a PID (process identifier).
[src:elixir/processes] At this point, the process you spawned is very likely dead.
[src:elixir/processes] Processes get much more interesting when we are able to send and receive messages.
[src:elixir/processes] When a message is sent to a process, the message is stored in the process mailbox.
[src:elixir/processes] The `receive/1` block goes through the current process mailbox searching for a message that matches any of the given patterns.
[src:elixir/processes] `receive/1` supports guards and many clauses, exactly as `case/2`.
[src:elixir/processes] The process that sends the message does not block on `send/2`, it puts the message in the recipient's mailbox and continues.
[src:elixir/processes] In particular, a process can send messages to itself.
[src:elixir/processes] If there is no message in the mailbox matching any of the patterns, the current process will wait until a matching message arrives.
[src:elixir/processes] A timeout of 0 can be given when you already expect the message to be in the mailbox.
[src:elixir/processes] The `inspect/1` function is used to convert a data structure's internal representation into a string, typically for printing.
[src:elixir/processes] Notice that when the `receive` block gets executed the sender process we have spawned may already be dead, as its only instruction was to send a message.
[src:elixir/processes] While in the shell, you may find the helper `flush/0` quite useful.
[src:elixir/processes] It flushes and prints all the messages in the mailbox.
[src:elixir/processes] The majority of times we spawn processes in Elixir, we spawn them as linked processes.
[src:elixir/processes] It merely logged an error but the parent process is still running.
[src:elixir/processes] If we want the failure in one process to propagate to another one, we should link them.
[src:elixir/processes] Because processes are linked, we now see a message saying the parent process, which is the shell process, has received an EXIT signal from another process causing the shell to terminate.
[src:elixir/processes] IEx detects this situation and starts a new shell session.
[src:elixir/processes] Linking can also be done manually by calling `Process.link/1`.
[src:elixir/processes] We recommend that you take a look at the `Process` module for other functionality provided by processes.
[src:elixir/processes] Processes and links play an important role when building fault-tolerant systems.
[src:elixir/processes] Elixir processes are isolated and don't share anything by default.
[src:elixir/processes] Therefore, a failure in a process will never crash or corrupt the state of another process.
[src:elixir/processes] Links, however, allow processes to establish a relationship in case of failure.
[src:elixir/processes] We often link our processes to supervisors which will detect when a process dies and start a new process in its place.
[src:elixir/processes] While other languages would require us to catch/handle exceptions, in Elixir we are actually fine with letting processes fail because we expect supervisors to properly restart our systems.
[src:elixir/processes] "Failing fast" (sometimes referred as "let it crash") is a common philosophy when writing Elixir software!
[src:elixir/processes] `spawn/1` and `spawn_link/1` are the basic primitives for creating processes in Elixir.
[src:elixir/processes] Although we have used them exclusively so far, most of the time we are going to use abstractions that build on top of them.
[src:elixir/processes] Let's see the most common one, called tasks.
[src:elixir/processes] Instead of `spawn/1` and `spawn_link/1`, we use `Task.start/1` and `Task.start_link/1` which return `{:ok, pid}` rather than just the PID.
[src:elixir/processes] This is what enables tasks to be used in supervision trees.
[src:elixir/processes] Furthermore, `Task` provides convenience functions, like `Task.async/1` and `Task.await/1`, and functionality to ease distribution.
[src:elixir/processes] We will explore tasks and other abstractions around processes in the "Mix and OTP guide".
[src:elixir/processes] If you are building an application that requires state, for example, to keep your application configuration, or you need to parse a file and keep it in memory, where would you store it?
[src:elixir/processes] Processes are the most common answer to this question.
[src:elixir/processes] We can write processes that loop infinitely, maintain state, and send and receive messages.
[src:elixir/processes] Note that the `start_link` function starts a new process that runs the `loop/1` function, starting with an empty map.
[src:elixir/processes] The `loop/1` (private) function then waits for messages and performs the appropriate action for each message.
[src:elixir/processes] We made `loop/1` private by using `defp` instead of `def`.
[src:elixir/processes] In the case of a `:get` message, it sends a message back to the caller and calls `loop/1` again, to wait for a new message.
[src:elixir/processes] While the `:put` message actually invokes `loop/1` with a new version of the map, with the given `key` and `value` stored.
[src:elixir/processes] At first, the process map has no keys, so sending a `:get` message and then flushing the current process inbox returns `nil`.
[src:elixir/processes] Notice how the process is keeping a state and we can get and update this state by sending the process messages.
[src:elixir/processes] In fact, any process that knows the `pid` above will be able to send it messages and manipulate the state.
[src:elixir/processes] Using processes to maintain state and name registration are very common patterns in Elixir applications.
[src:elixir/processes] However, most of the time, we won't implement those patterns manually as above, but by using one of the many abstractions that ship with Elixir.
[src:elixir/processes] For example, Elixir provides `Agent`s, which are simple abstractions around state.
[src:elixir/processes] A `:name` option could also be given to `Agent.start_link/2` and it would be automatically registered.
[src:elixir/processes] Besides agents, Elixir provides an API for building generic servers (called `GenServer`), registries, and more, all powered by processes underneath.
[src:elixir/processes] Those, along with supervision trees, will be explored with more detail in the "Mix and OTP guide", which will build a complete Elixir application from start to finish.
[src:elixir/processes] For now, let's move on and explore the world of I/O in Elixir.
